Cross-Modal Learning for Chemistry Property Prediction: Large Language Models Meet Graph Machine Learning

Sakhinana Sagar Srinivas, Venkataramana Runkana
TCS Research
sagar.sakhinana@tcs.com, venkat.runkana@tcs.com Designed and programmed research, conducted experiments, analyzed results, and drafted manuscript
Abstract

In the field of chemistry, the objective is to create novel molecules with desired properties, facilitating accurate property predictions for applications such as material design and drug screening. However, existing graph deep learning methods face limitations that curb their expressive power. To address this, we explore the integration of vast molecular domain knowledge from Large Language Models (LLMs) with the complementary strengths of Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) to enhance performance in property prediction tasks. We introduce a Multi-Modal Fusion (MMF) framework that synergistically harnesses the analytical prowess of GNNs and the linguistic generative and predictive abilities of LLMs, thereby improving accuracy and robustness in predicting molecular properties. Our framework combines the effectiveness of GNNs in modeling graph-structured data with the zero-shot and few-shot learning capabilities of LLMs, enabling improved predictions while reducing the risk of overfitting. Furthermore, our approach effectively addresses distributional shifts, a common challenge in real-world applications, and showcases the efficacy of learning cross-modal representations, surpassing state-of-the-art baselines on benchmark datasets for property prediction tasks.

1 Introduction

Deep learning has great potential for efficiently predicting molecular properties compared to traditional methods, resulting in reduced computational complexity and costs. Recently, there has been a growing surge of interest in representing organic molecules as molecular graphs. Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) can learn patterns from these highly non-linear molecular topological structures, which find applications in various domains, including drug discovery[51, 54], material design[38, 45], and environmental science[63, 49]. Several state-of-the-art graph machine learning algorithms are available in the literature, including MPNN[18], SchNet[44], E(n)-GNN[43], DimeNet++[16], and SphereNet[32]. GNNs have been extensively studied for molecular property applications; however, they suffer from bottlenecks such as limited expressive power[26], over-squashing[12], and over-smoothing[41] issues. In recent years, Large Language Models (LLMs)[5, 8, 48] have revolutionized the field of natural language processing with improved performance in various tasks, generating human-like responses, facilitating complex logical reasoning, and demonstrating capabilities in multitasking and multi-modal learning. Zero-Shot Chain of Thought[57](for brevity, Zero-Shot CoT) and Few-shot (In-Context) Learning[5](for brevity, Few-Shot ICL) are prompt engineering strategies for utilizing LLMs in specific linguistic tasks or related problem-solving scenarios. Zero-Shot CoT relies on task-specific instructions without demonstrations, requiring the language model to generalize from the implicit knowledge embedded within its parameters, which was learned from the training data, to generate the output. Conversely, Few-Shot ICL includes a few guiding demonstrations along with the instructions in the prompts, fostering contextual understanding and task-specific adaptation. Despite the progress in the application of foundational LLMs across various scientific disciplines, integrating LLMs with GNNs for the task of molecule property prediction remains an underexplored area. However, this presents an opportunity for innovative techniques that combine LLMs and GNNs to enhance property prediction applications. GNNs are effective at modeling the complex, graph-structured molecular data, capturing the structural and feature characteristics of graphs. Meanwhile, LLMs can encode molecular information implicitly within their parameters, owing to their training on extensive and diverse text corpora. LLMs can provide linguistic insights rich in domain-specific knowledge that serve as auxiliary information, bolstering property prediction tasks. The goal is to leverage the complementary strengths of both LLMs and GNNs to create a more robust and accurate predictive framework. In this study, we introduce a novel multi-modal fusion framework, MMF, that integrates the complementary analytical capabilities of GNNs and linguistic comprehension of LLMs within an end-to-end design to enhance the accuracy and robustness of molecular predictions. This framework achieves superior performance in chemical property prediction compared to state-of-the-art baselines, thereby reducing the risk of overfitting and potentially accelerating both the training and inference processes. Overall, this work introduces the subsequent contributions, outlined as follows:

  • •

    We propose a multi-faceted semantic fusion approach to obtain cross-modal embeddings, which combines Zero-shot LLMs prompting with graph neural networks (GNNs). We employ a five-step approach to generate cross-modal embeddings for molecular graphs: (a) First, we use custom CoT prompts, which include task-specific instructions to query LLMs in a zero-shot setting to generate technical descriptions on various aspects of the chemical SMILES representations, such as functional groups and chemical properties. (b) Next, we fine-tune small-scale language models (LMs) using the generated technical descriptions for domain-specific customization to compute context-aware token embeddings. (c) Then, we employ a softmax attention pooling mechanism to compute text-level embeddings from the contextualized token embeddings to encapsulate the rich domain-specific knowledge in the generated textual descriptions. (d) Independently and in parallel, we utilize pre-existing GNNs — specifically, Chebyshev Graph Convolution (CGC)[9, 20] — to interpret complex, graph-structured molecular data to compute molecular graph-level embeddings. (e) Finally, we use a cross-modal multi-head attention mechanism[52] to integrate the graph and text-level embeddings, offering a robust and efficient framework for generating semantically enriched cross-modal embeddings that effectively bridge structured and unstructured data.

  • •

    We propose ICL for the few-shot molecular property prediction task with LLMs. We leverage ICL to guide LLMs in predicting molecular properties without the necessity of explicit fine-tuning on labeled data. Utilizing context-augmented prompts — which comprise task-specific instructions and demonstrations (input-output mappings, in SMILES notation for molecules and their properties) — Our method queries LLMs to generate and transform predictions into a prediction embedding. It capitalizes on the implicit knowledge embedded within the pretrained parameters of LLMs, enabling it to make accurate predictions for new, unseen molecules, conditioned on the context-augmented prompt.

  • •

    We use the Mixture-of-Experts (MOE) method with a gating mechanism at the output layer for high-precision molecule property prediction. Two types of embeddings, cross-modal and prediction embeddings, are integrated into a unified embedding using a gating mechanism that dynamically allocates weights to each embedding based on their predictive performance. The framework’s training objectives are twofold: first, to optimize the weight distribution of each embedding to accurately predict the ground-truth molecular properties; second, to fine-tune the embeddings based on this weight distribution. Overall, the framework aims to leverage the strengths of multiple learning strategies to achieve high-precision predictions for molecular properties.

Experiments were conducted using six publicly available molecule property prediction datasets to evaluate the performance of the MMF framework, with consistent results demonstrating its effectiveness in accurately predicting properties across all benchmark datasets. In summary, we present a cohesive and multifaceted framework that integrates advanced computational approaches and learning strategies to enhance precision and efficiency in molecular property predictions, potentially fostering advancements in molecular science and technology. 2.2 Graph Chebyshev Convolution

Graph Convolutional Networks (GCNs) are designed to learn from graph data. They can be categorized into spatial and spectral approaches. The spatial GCN analyzes node neighborhoods. The spectral GCN, grounded in the spectral graph theory, uses the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of the graph’s Laplacian matrix for convolutions. The spectral convolution[6] is computationally expensive and inherently non-local. Graph Chebyshev convolution(CGC, [9, 20]) is a scalable alternative to spectral convolution that offers locality in capturing local-graph-based features, flexibility in approximating spectral properties, and scalability through recursive Laplacian computation. CGC operator utilizes Chebyshev polynomials to approximate spectral graph convolution, enabling the application of convolutional filters on graph-structured data by approximating the graph Laplacian with Chebyshev polynomials. Chebyshev polynomials are obtained from the normalized Laplacian matrix of a graph, L^=D^−1/2​𝒢^A​D^−1/2^𝐿superscript^𝐷12subscript^𝒢𝐴superscript^𝐷12\hat{L}=\hat{D}^{-1/2}\hat{\mathcal{G}}_{A}\hat{D}^{-1/2}, where 𝒢^Asubscript^𝒢𝐴\hat{\mathcal{G}}_{A} is the normalized adjacency matrix and D^^𝐷\hat{D} is the diagonal degree matrix. The Chebyshev approximation approximates the graph Laplacian using Chebyshev polynomials, designated as Tk​(L^)subscript𝑇𝑘^𝐿T_{k}(\hat{L}), calculated through a recurrence relation described as,

2.3 Language Models

In recent years, the introduction of pre-trained large language models (LLMs), such as ChatGPT[5], Google’s PaLM[8], and Meta’s LLaMA[48], has had a transformative impact in the domain of language modeling, enhancing performance and capabilities across a wide range of NLP tasks and applications. The LLMs adopt a ‘pre-train, prompt, and predict’ approach, attaining vast linguistic understanding through pre-training and generating human-like responses with tailored prompts[57, 61]. Smaller pre-trained language models (LMs), such as BERT[11] and DeBERTa[21], lack the sophisticated logical reasoning abilities of LLMs. However, they offer advantages such as access to logits or token embeddings, which aid in explainability for downstream applications utilizing the pre-trained LM models. In addition, these small-scale LMs can be fine-tuned with labeled data in an affordable manner for domain-specific customization. However, LLMs are resource-intensive to fine-tune with labeled data for task adaptation due to their high model complexity, making them less accessible to low-budget research labs. Additionally, the black-box nature of these large language models limits interpretability in downstream applications by not providing access to latent token embeddings or logits. To address these challenges, Language Modeling as a Service (LMaaS[46]) allows text-based API access to LLMs avoiding the high computational costs of domain-specific customization through fine-tuning. While it may seem intuitive to use LLMs for interpreting chemical SMILES strings, the study of their effectiveness in predicting molecular properties is still in its early stages. LLMs have been proven to be effective at zero-shot learning and (in-context) few-shot learning across a diverse set of tasks in the field of NLP. We refer to the method of conditioning the language model as ‘prompting’. Prompts with explicit conditioning based on task-specific instructions and a few demonstrations are termed as ‘few-shot prompts’, while those that rely solely on task-specific instructions are referred to as ‘zero-shot prompts’. In our molecular property prediction task, we focus on the development and exploration of various hand-crafted prompt engineering strategies. These include the zero-shot chain-of-thought (Zero-Shot CoT) and few-shot (in-context) learning (Few-Shot ICL), which aid in conditioning the LLMs to adapt to new tasks either through instructions that describe the task (zero-shot) without prior labeled data or through task-specific instructions accompanied by demonstrations(input-output pairs, i.e., few-shot). In our framework, we utilize LLMs in both zero-shot and few-shot learning scenarios, each serving a different purpose. (a) Our approach employs customized CoT prompts to query general-purpose LLMs in a zero-shot setting, generating textual descriptions that encapsulate various aspects of organic molecules, including molecular structure, physical properties, applications, and more. We fine-tune small-scale pre-trained LMs using these technical descriptions, then compute text-level embeddings using a softmax attention pooling mechanism to encapsulate the specialized knowledge in the technical descriptions, which is critical for downstream property prediction tasks. (b) We use (in-context) few-shot prompting of LLMs for molecular property prediction by leveraging input-output mappings (chemical SMILES strings — molecular properties pairs) in the context-augmented prompts. The ICL approach exploits the inherent knowledge of LLMs, conditioning on the augmented prompt to accurately predict molecular properties for new, unseen molecules, without the need for explicit fine-tuning.

Evaluation LLMs & LMs:

In our work, we employ three representative LLMs: text-davinci-003, ChatGPT, and BARD. Table 1 summarizes the main characteristics of the LLMs. Text-davinci-003, a GPT-3 model from OpenAI, excels in numerous natural language tasks, particularly zero-shot and few-shot instruction-following tasks. GPT-3.5-turbo, a refined variant within the GPT-3.5 model family, is widely recognized for its exceptional performance and cost-effectiveness. Meanwhile, Google’s BARD111https://bard.google.com, a recently updated chatbot featuring a new large language model (LLM) known as PaLM 2[3], stands out due to its significantly larger parameter count and expanded vocabulary size compared to the models in the GPT-3.5 family. In the Google Bard and GPT model family, two parameters — Top-p (also known as nucleus sampling or probabilistic sampling) and temperature — are crucial for controlling text generation. Specifically, Top-p governs the diversity of generated text, while the temperature parameter influences the randomness of the language models during text generation. The Top-p parameter sets a probability threshold for including a token in the generated sentence, serving as a sampling method that prevents the language model from generating tokens that are either too rare or too common. Conversely, the temperature parameter modulates the randomness of the generated text: a higher temperature leads to more random text, whereas a lower temperature results in more deterministic text. In our experiments, we set the Top-p and temperature parameters to one and zero, respectively, to retrieve factual and accurate textual outputs. Additionally, we utilized a pre-trained small-scale language model known as DeBERTa222For more information, refer to the DeBERTa model documentation available at https://huggingface.co/docs/transformers/index.[21]. In a zero-shot setting, LLMs generate technical descriptions about chemical SMILES strings, while small-scale language models encode rich knowledge in textual descriptions for task-specific customization, enhancing the performance of the framework in property prediction tasks. In contrast, we employ few-shot prompting of LLMs to predict molecular properties.

Zero-short LLM Prompting:

We access LLMs through LMaaS platforms[46] via text-based API interactions. We utilize a standardized chain-of-thoughts (CoT) prompt template to query LLMs in a zero-shot setting, aiming to glean linguistic insights into the specialized knowledge of chemical SMILES strings, including their structure and physical properties, among others. The generated technical descriptions serve as auxiliary information for downstream applications. Fine-Tuning LMs and Domain-Specific Customization:

In our approach, we utilize a small-scale pre-trained language model (LM) to encode the text outputs generated by a larger language model (LLM). During fine-tuning, the smaller LM extracts informative features from the generated descriptions for task-specific customization. The small-scale LM serves as an intermediate layer between LLMs and downstream prediction layers. Few-Shot LLM Prompting:

In-Context Learning (ICL) enables LLMs to adapt to new tasks without the need for explicit, gradient-based fine-tuning[5] on labeled data. This approach allows LLMs to learn through analogy, utilizing just a few input-output pairs specific to the downstream task. ICL leverages the implicit knowledge embedded in pre-trained LLM parameters to adapt to new tasks through task-specific demonstrations, thereby avoiding the need to repurpose LLMs with parameter updates. The context-augmented prompt provides task-specific instructions and demonstrations (input-output mappings), enabling LLMs to generate outputs conditioned on the prompt for improved generalization performance. In the case of molecular graph property prediction tasks, ICL involves constructing a context-augmented prompt using a few input-output pairs (𝒢i,𝒫i)subscript𝒢𝑖subscript𝒫𝑖(\mathcal{G}_{i},\mathcal{P}_{i}) sampled from the training data and the task-specific instruction is related to the query SMILES representation. At inference time, on test input 𝒢testsubscript𝒢test\mathcal{G}_{\text{test}}, ICL generates the output based on the conditional probability distribution, 𝒫test∼𝐏​(𝒫test∣(𝒢train,𝒫train),𝒢test)similar-tosubscript𝒫test𝐏conditionalsubscript𝒫testsubscript𝒢trainsubscript𝒫trainsubscript𝒢test\mathcal{P}_{\text{test}}\sim\mathbf{P}(\mathcal{P}_{\text{test}}\mid(\mathcal{G}_{\text{train}},\mathcal{P}_{\text{train}}),\mathcal{G}_{\text{test}}), where ∼similar-to\sim denotes the decoding strategy. To examine how the quality and quantity of ICL demonstrations impact the performance of property prediction tasks, we investigate two distinct ICL sampling strategies. We explore two distinct ICL sampling strategies: “Random” and “Scaffold”. The quality of demonstrations is determined by the sampling strategies used to identify the top-K𝐾K chemical SMILES representations that are most similar to the query SMILES representation. To investigate the impact of the quantity of ICL demonstrations on performance, we optimize the number of ICL demonstrations (K𝐾K) for each query SMILES representation. In the random strategy, we randomly sample K𝐾K input-output pairs from the training data. In contrast, the Scaffold strategy employs Tanimoto similarity [47] based on Morgan fingerprints [36] with a radius of 2, to identify the top-K𝐾K most similar chemical SMILES representations to a given query SMILES representation within the training data. We employ two sampling strategies to construct an augmented prompt for analyzing the effectiveness of ICL demonstrations on property prediction tasks. In summary, our goal is to task LLMs with a contextual prompt. This prompt comprises a list of input-output pairs, where the input represents an organic molecule in SMILES notation, and the output denotes its molecular properties along with task-specific instructions. The instruction in the context-augmented prompt directs LLMs to predict the multiple molecular properties of the query SMILES representation. This task will demonstrate the LLM’s ability to predict these properties based on its inherent knowledge, simply by conditioning on the prompt, without any parameter updates. This approach stands in contrast to supervised learning, where parameter updates are performed to fine-tune models based on labeled data, enabling them to predict the properties of new, unseen molecules. For each query SMILES representation, the PLLMs generate a c𝑐c-dimensional vector hpredi∈ℝcsubscriptℎsubscriptpred𝑖superscriptℝ𝑐h_{\text{pred}_{i}}\in\mathbb{R}^{c}, where c𝑐c signifies the dimension associated with the multiple properties to be predicted. This vector is linearly encoded into a high-dimensional space to produce a prediction embedding hICLi∈ℝdsubscriptℎsubscriptICL𝑖superscriptℝ𝑑h_{\text{ICL}_{i}}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}, which encapsulates the LLMs’ predictions. 2.4 Cross-modal Attention Layer

We compute the cross-modal embedding hifsubscriptsuperscriptℎ𝑓𝑖h^{f}_{i} through a multi-head attention mechanism[52] that integrates the graph-level embeddings hgisubscriptℎsubscript𝑔𝑖h_{g_{i}} and text-level embeddings htextisubscriptℎsubscripttext𝑖h_{\text{text}_{i}}. The multi-head attention(MHA) mechanism offers a robust framework for integrating cross-domain embeddings, facilitating multi-faceted analysis in the context of interpreting correlations between molecular structures and properties. (a) Richer Representation: The multi-head attention mechanism enables the computation of a richer, multi-faceted representation for each molecule. It allows each attention head to focus on different facets, such as chemical bonds or functional groups in the molecular structure. Meanwhile, other heads attend to corresponding textual descriptions, like reactivity or the physicochemical properties of the observed functional group. (b) Semantic Matching: Additionally, the multi-head mechanism facilitates semantic matching, as individual heads can specialize in aligning various semantic aspects, such as specific functional groups in the molecular graph with their corresponding textual descriptions. For example, one attention head might specialize in aligning aromatic rings in the molecular structure with textual descriptions related to aromaticity. This allows the model to effectively integrate different types of molecular information, providing a contextual and comprehensive view of both text and graph data. (c) Enhanced Context Sensitivity: Finally, the multi-head mechanism enhances context sensitivity. Molecules often behave differently depending on their context. For instance, a molecule’s reactivity can change based on its surrounding environment, and this information might be captured in textual descriptions. Multi-head attention allows the model to be sensitive to this context by considering both the graph-level embeddings and the text-level descriptions in tandem. This could be particularly beneficial for complex tasks. In summary, MHA mechanism for computing cross-modal embeddings facilitates a rich, nuanced representation of molecules by allowing parallel focus on various facets of data, including molecular graph structures and textual descriptions. It enhances semantic matching by aligning different semantic features from both text and graph data, and improves context sensitivity, enabling the model to understand and adapt to the dynamic behaviors of molecules in different contexts. Moreover, the MHA mechanism improves computational efficiency through parallel processing across heads, and its modular nature makes it easy to adapt and extend. It also offers benefits such as increased model capacity, and better generalization to unseen data. Overall, multi-head attention provides a robust and versatile framework for seamlessly fusing information across different modalities. 2.5 Output Layer

In this framework, we utilize the mixture-of-experts (MOE) technique with a gating mechanism for the output layer. In the context of this framework, the MOE mechanism is a competitive game where each embedding — either cross-modal embeddings obtained from the multi-head attention mechanism (integrating zero-shot LLM prompting & GNNs outputs) or prediction embeddings from few-shot LLM prompting — aims to maximize its contribution to the final prediction. Unlike a cooperative game, each embedding aims to outperform the others for a larger weight from the gating mechanism. The gating mechanism allocates weights based on individual performance, creating a competitive landscape where more accurate embeddings gain greater influence. This competition can drive the framework towards a globally optimal solution. The embeddings are combined by the gating mechanism, which allocates input-dependent weights to calculate a weighted sum of embeddings. Training in this framework aims to: a) determine the optimal weight distribution for precise predictions of ground-truth molecular properties, and b) optimize the embeddings jointly according to the weight distribution specified by the gating mechanism. The unified embeddings are obtained by merging embeddings using input-dependent weights allocated by the gating mechanism as follows,

g𝑔\displaystyle g =σ​(fs​(hif)+fg​(hICLi))absent𝜎subscript𝑓𝑠subscriptsuperscriptℎ𝑓𝑖subscript𝑓𝑔subscriptℎsubscriptICL𝑖\displaystyle=\sigma\big{(}f_{s}(h^{f}_{i})+f_{g}(h_{\text{ICL}_{i}})\big{)} (13)
𝐡usubscript𝐡𝑢\displaystyle\mathbf{h}_{u} =σ​(g​(hif)+(1−g)​(hICLi))absent𝜎𝑔subscriptsuperscriptℎ𝑓𝑖1𝑔subscriptℎsubscriptICL𝑖\displaystyle=\sigma\big{(}g(h^{f}_{i})+(1-g)(h_{\text{ICL}_{i}})\big{)} (14)

3 Experiments and Results

3.1 Datasets and Experimental Setup

The QM8[40] and QM9[39] are two large datasets of quantum chemical properties for low-tree width organic molecules, which serve as benchmarks and training data for ML models in the field of quantum chemistry property prediction task. The QM8 dataset comprises 21,786 molecules containing up to 8 heavy atoms, namely C, O, N, or F. It provides properties such as electronic excitation energies, oscillator strengths, and ionization potentials. In comparison, the QM9 dataset is larger, consisting of 133,885 molecules with up to 9 heavy atoms, including properties like atomization energy, HOMO/LUMO gap, dipole moment, and polarizability. Both datasets are split into training, validation, and test sets. The training set is used to fit the model parameters, the validation set is used to select the best hyperparameters, and the test set is used to evaluate the model’s generalization performance. The quantum properties were standardized to have zero mean and unit variance. The predictions were then re-normalized to the original scale to calculate the error metric. In this work, our framework integrates both large language models (LLMs) and smaller language models (LMs). We focus on employing zero-shot CoT and few-shot ICL learning techniques to prompt LLMs for the molecule prediction task without the need for retraining or finetuning. We achieve this by using a LMaaS platform[46] to access frozen trainable parameters of LLMs through text-based API interactions. The hyperparameters of this framework were set to a batch size of 32, 50 epochs for training, and a hidden or embedding dimension of 128. We conducted our experiments using the following four large language models (LLMs): GPT-4.0, GPT-3.5-turbo, GPT-3.0-text-davinci-003, and Google Bard. We did not fine-tune the hyperparameters of our framework for each LLM. Instead, we utilized the same hyperparameters across all LLMs. This shows that our framework is general and easy to use, and that it can utilize any off-the-shelf LLMs. To optimize the use of computational resources, we utilized 8 V100 GPUs, each equipped with 8 GB of GPU memory, for the training of deep learning models built upon the PyTorch framework. The LLMs have a context length limitation with a maximum sequence length of 4096 tokens for GPT models and 4000 tokens for Google Bard. The Adam optimizer[23] was used to train the framework, starting with a learning rate of 1​e−31superscript𝑒31e^{-3}. A learning rate decay scheduler was employed to reduce the learning rate by half if the validation loss did not improve for 7 epochs, and early stopping was implemented to prevent overfitting on the training set. For few-shot learning, we utilized the scaffold technique with a hyperparameter K𝐾K set to 16 for sampling demonstrations to construct context-augmented prompts. The framework’s performance was evaluated using the MAE metric, and the results were presented on the test datasets. Three independent experiments were conducted, and we report the average.

4 Conclusion

In the rapidly evolving field of computational chemistry, the pressing need for methodologies with higher accuracy and robustness in predicting molecular properties is undeniable. Our pioneering efforts in this study have introduced the Multi-Modal Fusion (MMF) framework, which synergistically amalgamates LLMs and GNNs to enhance the accuracy of molecular property predictions. Our approach not only improves predictions but also reduces the likelihood of overfitting, surpassing existing benchmarks in property prediction tasks. Our results on benchmark datasets confirm our hypothesis that fusing information from text and graph-based modalities can significantly enhance performance. This breakthrough opens new avenues for scientific discovery, advancing computational chemistry applications across domains to shape the next generation of tools and insights in chemistry.

5.3 Ablation Study

Our proposed framework obtains unified embeddings by integrating knowledge from Zero-Shot

CoT and Few-Shot ICL learning methods, utilizing prompting based on LLMs (refer to Subsection 2.3) and GNNs (refer to Subsection 2.2). We conducted ablation studies to examine the impact of each method on the overall enhanced performance of our framework. By selectively disabling methods, we created multiple ablated variants of our framework and evaluated them using benchmark datasets for the property prediction task. This approach enabled us determine the contributions of the disabled methods to the overall framework performance. We chose the proposed MMF framework as the reference baseline for the ablation studies. This rigorous approach not only validates the effectiveness of the different methods but also provides justification for their design choices and inclusion within the framework. Our proposed framework operates through a multi-step pipeline, as follows:

  • ✓

    Synergistic Cross-Modal Embedding Generation (SEG): The Zero-Shot CoT prompts LLMs to generate technical descriptions of chemical SMILES representations. These descriptions are then used to fine-tune smaller LMs for domain-specific customization, facilitating the computation of context-aware token embeddings. We utilize softmax attention pooling to obtain text-level embeddings from these contextualized token embeddings. Simultaneously and in parallel, the Graph Chebyshev Convolution operator computes graph-level embeddings. These two sets of embeddings are synergistically integrated using a multi-head attention mechanism, thereby establishing a robust framework for integrating structured and unstructured data.

  • ✓

    Predictive Embedding Generation (PEG): The Few-Shot ICL method prompts LLMs to predict molecular properties based on a few demonstrations of the downstream task, which are then subsequently encoded to obtain prediction embeddings. ICL guides predictions without requiring explicit fine-tuning, relying solely on the implicit pre-trained knowledge encapsulated within the LLMs’ parameters, and conditioned on the context-augmented prompts.

  • ✓

    MOE Dynamic Prediction (MOE-DP): For the output layer, we employ the MOE technique with a gating mechanism, where cross-modal and prediction embeddings are unified through the gating mechanism. The goal is to optimize predictive performance and fine-tune the embeddings, leveraging diverse learning strategies for precise molecular property predictions.

The ablated variants without the synergistic embedding generation (SEG), predictive embedding generation (PEG), and MOE dynamic prediction (MOE-DP) methods are referred to as ‘w/o SEG,’ ‘w/o PEG,’ and ‘w/o MOE-DP,’ respectively. In the case of ‘w/o MOE-DP,’ we utilize a linear operator to predict the molecular properties. The experimental findings from the ablation study are shown in Tables 8 and 9. All experiments were conducted using the scaffold technique with K𝐾K=16. In the ablation study focusing on molecular property estimation, we evaluated the performance of the ablated variants against the baseline using the MAE error metric, allowing for a comprehensive analysis. Upon examination, it becomes evident that the synergistic embedding generation (SEG) method within the MMF framework holds greater significance than the predictive embedding generation (PEG) and MOE dynamic prediction (MOE-DP) methods for attaining state-of-the-art performance on the benchmark datasets. For the QM8 dataset, the ‘w/o SEG’ variant shows a substantial decline in performance relative to the baseline, as evidenced by a marked increase of 46.44%percent46.4446.44\% in MAE. In contrast, the ‘w/o PEG’ variant exhibits marginally inferior performance compared to the baseline, with a modest increase of 14.49%percent14.4914.49\% in MAE. Similarly, the ‘w/o MOE-DP’ variant performs much worse than the baseline, with an increase of 20.41%percent20.4120.41\% in MAE. This increase in error might be attributed to the substitution with an oversimplified linear operator in the output layer. Similar trends were observed in the QM9 dataset. The higher increase in the performance metrics of the ablated variants, when compared to the baseline, underscores the relative significance of the mechanisms underpinning the omitted methods of the baseline. The experimental findings suggest that integrating knowledge from both text and graph modalities is a promising approach for enhancing the overall performance of the framework. Specifically, our innovative framework leverages a fusion of deep learning techniques, including GNNs and both larger and smaller language models, to predict molecular properties. The zero-shot CoT prompting of LLMs generates technical descriptions of molecules, which are then encoded by smaller language models to generate text-level embeddings. These text-level embeddings are seamlessly integrated with graph embeddings, resulting in improved cross-modal embeddings. We jointly optimize the cross-modal embeddings and the prediction embeddings generated by the few-shot ICL prompting of LLMs through a MOE technique with gating mechanism and then combine them to enhance the performance of our framework. In conclusion, this holistic approach not only demonstrates the benefits of combining diverse knowledge sources for optimized molecular property predictions but also provides a comprehensive understanding of molecular representations, setting a benchmark in the domain.

5.4.1 Impact of Synergistic Cross-Modal Embedding Generation(SEG) method

The synergistic embedding generation(SEG) method consists of three main components:

  • ✓

    Text-Level Embeddings (TL-Emb): Computed using softmax attention pooling of contextual token embeddings. These context-aware embeddings are obtained from fine-tuning smaller LMs on the technical descriptions generated by the zero-shot CoT prompting of LLMs on chemical SMILES representations.

  • ✓

    Graph-Level Embeddings (GL-Emb): Computed through Graph Chebyshev Convolution technique on the corresponding non-linear molecular graph representations obtained from the chemical SMILES representations.

  • ✓

    Cross-Modal Embeddings (CM-Emb): Computed using a multi-head attention mechanism to facilitate the robust integration and analysis of text-level and graph-level embeddings.

We conducted ablation studies to examine the impact of different embeddings within the Synergistic Embedding Generation (SEG) method on the overall improved performance of our framework. The ablated variants without the text-level embeddings (TL-Emb), graph-level embeddings (GL-Emb), and cross-modal embeddings (CM-Emb) methods are referred to as ‘w/o TL-Emb’, ‘w/o GL-Emb’, and ‘w/o CM-Emb’, respectively. In the case of ‘w/o CM-Emb’, we concatenate the embeddings and utilize a linear operator to predict the cross-modal embeddings. The experimental findings from the ablation study are presented in Tables 10 and 11.

Upon closer examination, it becomes evident that text-level embeddings (TL-Emb) are more significant than graph-level embeddings (GL-Emb) in achieving state-of-the-art performance on the benchmark datasets. For the QM8 dataset, the ‘w/o TL-Emb’ variant demonstrates a substantial decline in performance compared to the baseline, as evidenced by a significant increase of 27.65%percent27.6527.65\% in MAE. In contrast, the ‘w/o GL-Emb’ variant exhibits only a marginally inferior performance compared to the baseline, with a modest increase of 9.53%percent9.539.53\% in MAE. The ‘w/o CM-Emb’ variant shows the poorest performance relative to the baseline with an increase of 37.85%percent37.8537.85\% in MAE. This increase in error may be attributed to the substitution of an oversimplified concatenation of text-level and graph-level embeddings, along with the utilization of a linear operator to predict the cross-modal embeddings. Similar trends were observed in the QM9 dataset. The greater increase in performance metrics for the ablated variants compared to the baseline underscores the relative significance of the omitted methods

5.4.2 Impact of Predictive Embedding Generation(PEG) method

In-context learning (ICL) or few-shot prompting enables pretrained foundational large language models (LLMs) to adapt to new tasks with only a few task-specific demonstrations, thus eliminating the need for parameter updates. This approach represents a departure from traditional supervised learning methods. In our study, we employ few-shot prompting with LLMs to predict molecular properties of new, unseen molecules. We construct context-augmented prompts, comprising task-specific instructions and demonstrations (inputs in the form of chemical SMILES strings and outputs as molecular property pairs) sampled from the training data to direct general-purpose LLMs in predicting molecular properties of the target chemical SMILES strings. In essence, the instruction serves to contextualize the task of predicting molecular properties for the target chemical SMILES strings, while the demonstrations are crucial in guiding the language model to produce relevant and accurate responses for the specific task at hand. In this scenario, the augmented prompt guides the LLMs to tap into the pre-existing knowledge embedded within their parameters, acquired during training on vast and diverse corpora, to predict the molecular graph properties. We explore two sampling strategies, "Random" and "Scaffold", to construct augmented prompts, and we evaluate the predictive abilities of LLMs that rely solely on these prompts. Our experiments focus on both the quality (how helpful are the demonstrations in reducing prediction error) and quantity (number of demonstrations) of these sampling methods, aiming to enhance property prediction accuracy.

Results:

Tables 12 and 13 present the MAE scores, showcasing the results of property prediction performance in our study on the impact of both quality and quantity of demonstrations during few-shot prompting of LLMs. Our analysis revealed that the MMF W/GPT models outperformed the MMF W/Google Bard in terms of MAE on both datasets under examination. Notably, among the evaluated MMF W/GPT models, MMF W/GPT-4 exhibited superior performance compared to MMF W/davinci-003 and MMF W/GPT-3.5 Turbo in predicting molecular properties. Our study supports the notion that increasing training examples in few-shot prompting(in-context learning) can significantly enhance framework performance. It underscores a direct correlation between the volume of ICL demonstrations and the predictive accuracy of the LLMs. Furthermore, our investigation provides compelling evidence that scaffold sampling consistently outperforms random sampling across distinct datasets (QM8 and QM9), further bolstering the empirical validity of our research. A possible reason for this might be the structural similarities between the molecules sampled from the scaffold strategy and the query molecule. This could potentially tilt the MMF GPT models towards making more precise decisions. LLMs still face a significant limitation in understanding molecular representations in SMILES strings, resulting in inaccurate results in property prediction tasks. SMILES notation is a widely used textual representation for chemical structures, but LLMs struggle to interpret it accurately due to issues like implicit hydrogen atoms, multiple valid representations for a single molecule, which leads to ambiguity, and treating SMILES strings as mere sequences of characters. This hampers the performance of LLMs in tasks such as property prediction and affects downstream cheminformatics tasks. Therefore, LLMs with improved capabilities in handling molecular structures and coupling with existing tools such as RDKit will be necessary.

5.5 Hyperparameter Tuning

Hyperparameters are parameters that are not learned from data but are set prior to the training process. They have a direct impact on the performance of the framework. To optimize the performance of our MMF framework, we conducted in-depth hyperparameter tuning through careful experimentation and analysis. We chose to use random search as an efficient method for exploring hyperparameters and identifying the best framework configuration on benchmark datasets, rather than employing computationally intensive methods like grid search or Bayesian optimization. This approach allowed us to achieve optimal performance on the test dataset across various benchmark datasets, as measured by the MAE metric. We identified a set of hyperparameters that significantly improved the MMF framework’s performance. We did not fine-tune large language models (LLMs) for the downstream property prediction task; instead, we accessed LLMs through text-based API interactions. We fine-tuned small-scale LMs using LLM-generated textual descriptions for the molecular property prediction task, while minimizing supervised regression loss. Hyperparameter optimization was performed on the MMF-W/GPT-4 variant of our framework. The key prioritized hyperparameters for this framework are batch size (b∈32,48,64𝑏324864b\in{32,48,64}) and hidden or embedding dimension (d∈64,128,196,256𝑑64128196256d\in{64,128,196,256}). Tables 14 and 15 present the results of hyperparameter tuning on representative benchmark datasets. We report the results for the near-optimal combinations of hyperparameters. All experiments were conducted using the GPT-4 framework with scaffold technique, setting K𝐾K=16. In summary, based on the experimental results presented in tables 14 and 15, the best hyperparameters for the MMF framework—particularly for the QM-8 dataset and many targets in the QM-9 dataset—appear to be a batch size (b𝑏b) of 32 and an embedding dimension (d𝑑d) of 128.

5.6 Large Language Models and Prompting

Large Language Models (LLMs) have brought about a paradigm shift in natural language processing for task adaptation with the ‘pre-train, prompt, and predict’ approach. This approach allows for more generalized adaptation to various tasks by using natural language instructions as prompts, without the need for extensive fine-tuning. It is flexible and efficient, enabling LLMs to perform a wide range of NLP tasks with minimal task-specific adaptation. This is achieved through demonstrations that allow LLMs to learn from analogy. Consequently, it has replaced the previously established ‘pre-train, fine-tune’ approach, which involves customizing the LLMs for each task through fine-tuning using task-specific labeled data. In this new paradigm, the LLM undergoes an initial phase of pre-training on a vast collection of unannotated text corpora without explicit human supervision. This process facilitates the learning of grammar, syntax, semantics, and even some level of common-sense reasoning, allowing the LLM to achieve improved linguistic comprehension and generate human-like responses. Instead of fine-tuning the language model with task-specific labeled data, as is customary in conventional approaches, this approach prompts the LLM with a natural language query that explicitly outlines the task and context. Based on this prompt, the LLM directly generates the desired output, using its pre-existing knowledge[30] embedded within its trainable parameters acquired during pretraining. A prompt is a textual input provided to an instruction-based or prompt-based language model to guide its behavior and generate desired outputs. It can take the form of a phrase, question, or sentence and may involve supplementary information or constraints. The prompt sets the context, provides instructions, and helps shape the LLM’s responses to align with the desired outcome. LLMs possess the ability to generate responses based on contextual information and prior training, allowing them to provide context-aware and coherent responses in conversations. Moreover, LLMs can be further customized and enhanced through fine-tuning, which involves using reinforcement learning techniques[37, 42] with human feedback to optimize their performance for specialized tasks or domains. This adaptability and versatility make LLMs powerful tools for a wide range of natural language processing applications. Consider an LLM, which accepts an input sequence of tokens x=(x1,x2,…,xn)𝑥subscript𝑥1subscript𝑥2…subscript𝑥𝑛x=(x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{n}) and outputs a token sequence y=(y1,y2,…,ym)𝑦subscript𝑦1subscript𝑦2…subscript𝑦𝑚y=(y_{1},y_{2},...,y_{m}). In summary, the prompt plays a crucial role in shaping the conditional probability distribution, as it provides relevant information and context to guide the generation of the desired output. Zero-shot prompting is a process in NLP in which large language models (LLMs), such as GPT-3.5 or Google Bard, are equipped to perform specific tasks without undergoing task-specific training. This ability is derived from their initial training on extensive and diverse text corpora, enabling them to access a broad spectrum of general knowledge. This method utilizes detailed, context-rich prompts to outline the task at hand, guiding the LLM to generate suitable responses based on its foundational knowledge, thereby demonstrating the language model’s zero-shot learning capabilities. Few-shot prompting is a technique in NLP that allows LLMs to perform a task with a few task-specific demonstrations. This is accomplished by first pre-training the LLM on a massive volume of text corpora, which allows it to learn a vast range of general knowledge. Then, the LLM is given a few task-specific input-output pairs and is trained to generate similar outputs. The LLM uses its pre-existing knowledge to generalize from the few demonstrations and learn to perform the task. In our work, we harness the zero-shot reasoning of LLMs, acquired through pre-training on vast text corpora. This empowers LLMs to enhance molecular graph-level embeddings from GNNs with richer textual information about molecular properties, reactivity, and more. This capability enables LLMs to tackle complex problems without requiring dedicated task-specific training.
